metadata.name: Life has no scores #108
metadata.description:
We cannot compose life, at best we hum along to the melodies that life has been played in front of us. Looking back at the scores of our lives, the notations are never neatly noted, but fully felt.  Rewinding the songs of life are our memories, whether sad, happy, angry, or melancholy. It is not clear whether I am dreaming or awake, but our songs all do end. 

In this final drop (for ?), I have reused the first ever class calligraphy(){} I have written from my genesis drop â€œNothing comes from nothingâ€. As time passes, 10 drops later, across almost to the year, I am grateful for the progress I have made, as an artist, and more importantly as a human. After all, what is behind the code of generative art is a human being. 

Scores of music, scrolls of calligraphy, calendar or diary, notating life, time passes, and changes are inevitable. Sometimes we sing louder in laughter and joy, sometimes we scribble in uneasiness, sometimes we just get lost in neon lights. Life goes on. You and me, all the same and yet different.  

There are too many friend artists, friend collectors, fxhash team members, to thank for helping me through this journey. I would like to pay homage to Rudxane in this work, who has taken me under his wings, mentoring and encouraging me in art as well as showing me some degen stuff on the side:-). This homage is not copy-minting, or copying of styles, which I do not have the coding skills to do so even if I wanted to. But it is the influence of taste in many works of Rudxane. In a vague but agreeable taste, I present to you Life has no scores. 

What I was taught was disrupted, and grid studies left unfinished, and oh do we have a BINGO?

Tested on Chrome. Other browsers may render different or not at all (firefox)

Press â€˜2â€™ to save png.

metadata.name: Cables and Clouds #75
metadata.description:
Capturing clouds... an old dream of mad scientist... coming true...
But wait... are they real clouds ? Maybe... maybe not...
Is it the real life ?
Is this just fantasy ?

Interaction.
Press h in live mode to list the possibilities.
Key 's'  : Save an image of the output at the current resolution
Key 1-9 : Change resolution
Key 'c' to change color palette
Key 'd' to toggle a special color mode to highlight the different components (and have the number of points used in your specific drawing).

Features.
18 different features displayed (format, color palettes, main elements characteristics, rare elements...).

metadata.name: Prophecy #318
metadata.description:
Elder Futhark Runes / Proto-Germanic alphabets flowing through the canvas.

Each iteration gets a random rune from 24 runes and the vector field angles are based on that.

Also picks one word from what the random rune symbolizes as a prophecy for the next year.

Minted for #fxhashturnsone event 18.11.2022.

50% of primary profits to Processing Foundation.

Load 2x or 4x dimensions (2560 * 3840px) image with '2' or '4'.

metadata.name: WaveForms #105
metadata.description:
The idea for WaveForms came to me in a dream: Sine waves constructed with stacks of dotted lines, the amount of dots per line fluctuating along another sine function and creating a phasing effect, then layering these waves can create all sorts of shading and gradient effects. I woke up, wrote everything I could in my notebook, polished a bit and here we are :)

Colors were chosen to bring a feeling of almost alien form: darker palettes, occasional pops of neon paired with the ribbed nature of the pattern can make it feel like some sort of sinister sci fi pop art, like I saw it in my dream.

Editions vary by amplitude, frequency, line mode, color mode, palette, background and accent color.

â€˜Orderâ€™ mode chooses the layered colors based on a set palette of 4 colors (of 16 palettes), while â€˜Chaosâ€™ chooses 4 colors of 64 total colors not limited by palette. Accent and Background colors are chosen as one of 64 as well. Chaos mode outputs can be much more interesting than their prebuilt counterparts, but do have the chance to result in flat imagery or unpleasing color palettes.

There is a 25% chance to output a â€œHappy Accidentâ€ mode image, which was a calculation error that has been made into a feature for sake of its extremely unpredictable behavior. 

Press â€™sâ€™ to save a .png (image size is tied to window height)

metadata.name: Planets #79
metadata.description:
A complete step aside from my normal work. I've been feeling nostalgic for old games and old science fiction recently. I wanted to bring those ideas together and create a feeling of comfort with this piece.

This generative token produces a random planet from a variety of types. Some are inspired by real planets, others by planets from fiction. Each planet can have moons or other nearby planets in the background. If the planet has its axis tilted it will have a summer and winter side, visible in its biomes. Very hot planets may have oceans only near the poles if at all, very cold planets may be frozen everywhere but the equator. 

Press down on the keyboard to see a map view in equirectangular projection.

And most of all enjoy your very own planet!

Celebrating getting old with Fx(hash).

Default image width = 2000px and aspect ratio = 4:3.

Background:
The canvas background texture is visible by default. This can be toggled off by adding â€œ&b=0â€ to the url.
The background scales with resolution to mimic a bigger canvas so it will look different at different resolutions.
At high resolutions a MoirÃ© pattern may appear on the canvas background texture due to the way images are resized in the browser. Itâ€™s always recommended to download a full resolution version of the piece.

metadata.name: Calmer waters - reissue #4
metadata.description:
This is a reissue of project #10669
https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/10669

I long for calmer waters. This piece is about that. It's a counterpoint. It reflects some of my best memories of the sea: the warm salty air on my face, interspersed with a cool breeze, leaving my lips salty tasting. The gentle rushing of the water. 

The sea with its vast panorama's can make you feel insignificant in the grand scheme of things. But this piece is about hope.
///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
About this reissue: An update of the security policy of fx(hash) blocks external scripts. This update stops malicious actors; they could try to interact with a userâ€™s wallet. So, this update is really a good thing. Itâ€™s a safeguard. However, due to this update the original project no longer loads in live view and after consultation and deliberation I decided to reissue the token without the use of external scripts (p5js). 

Only holders of the original project are on the allow list. 

Royalties are for the minter.

metadata.name: BINARY WORDS #214
metadata.description:
I drew my first 8x8 pixel binary image on 11/08/2022 with 'iloveyou' encoded for my wife, it was our 10-year anniversary on this day.  After that made this generative stuff for fxhash's birthday bash.

#fxhashturnsone

Donations:
25% to ThreeJs team

The image contains a binary coded word or phrase with a length of 8 characters. The grays represents 0, the other colors represents 1. One row -> one character. Should be proceed decoding from left to right and from top to bottom.

An example: 'iloveyou'

01101001
01101100
01101111
01110110
01100101
01111001
01101111
01110101

The fxrandom selects a word and the program converts it to binary data. After that, the background (ground and sky) is randomly generated from color schemes. Then the binary gray colors are drawn. Also the color of light next to null colors is randomly generated from color schemes. Random affects also the animation.

The animation stops when you do these interactions below, then restarts after a few seconds of inactivity.

Press spacebar to change:

- frame view -> without frame
- without frame -> original 8x8px size
- original 8x8px size -> frame view

Press 's' to save an svg from current view.

Notes:
- Build with ReactJs and TweenJs
- Every upcoming day, half of the remaining pieces are burned.

Happy Birthday fxhash community!
I'm glad to be among you!

metadata.name: Verdant Brut #164
metadata.description:
Verdant translates to â€œlush, greenâ€ and Brut means â€œdry, raw, or unrefined.â€

This series is less about impressions of nature, or vegetal growthâ€¦ but rather the vibrant, lush world that abstract art can provide and while certain iterations may serve Brutalist aesthetics, it tries to focus on the unrefined/raw aspect of the definition with more fluid shapes that feel irregular and organic in a playful, almost adolescent way.

Palettes inspired by MOMO, Melissa Wiederrecht, Erik Swahn, Marcelo Soria-RodrÃ­guez, Paul Klee, Mareva Millarc, Ernst Mether-BorgstroÌˆm, Douglas Herbert Courtenay Auburn, Jim Harris, Alayne Spafford, Man Ray, Lajos Kassak and William Lachance. While the palettes may not always reflect their trademark colors (if they even have any) they are an homage to individual pieces by the respective artists that have influenced this series in their own way.

4878 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries.

For more info on the chosen palettes and other inspirations, see article linked from the main project page: Regarding Verdant Brut

In live mode:
â€˜Sâ€™ : save as png (2376â€ŠÃ—â€Š3360)
â€™Vâ€™ : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
â€˜g=nâ€™ : no grain
â€˜g=pâ€™ : paper grain
â€˜h=tâ€™ : high resolution mode, 5940â€ŠÃ—â€Š8400 (Chrome only)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append â€œ&g=p&h=tâ€ to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save the png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: Stepping Stones #630
metadata.description:
"Stepping Stones" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Performance in Code: Deciphering Value in Generative Art, Art Basel Miami Beach, 2022

Stepping Stones explores the idea that the whole is greater than the sum of its parts. Simple patterns, shapes, textures, and colors are arranged in randomly selected ways. Overlaying shapes distort and blend, breaking these objects apart and causing complex forms to emerge. Combining these individual features together results in varying outcomes, from surprisingly simple to wildly chaotic.

---------------

Controls:
Press 1-6 to change the scale of the canvas (1 = default, 2500px x 2500px, 6 = 15,000px x 15,000px)
S (or double tap on mobile): Save output at current size
C: Toggle cutout shapes visibility
H: Toggle cutout outlines visibility
B: Iterate border sizes (none, default, 1.5x, 2x, 3x)
T: Toggle texture visibility
F: Toggle fullscreen
Add the url params x and y to set custom dimensions. For example, add &x=1500&y=500 for a 1500px x 500px image

---------------

Tyler Boswell (@teaboswell) 2022
